    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>VIDEOTAPE IN CIVIL COURT</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By John Holl</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Holl, John</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>New Jersey Supreme Court committee issues rules restricting more than one civil trial postponement if expert witnesses are not available, after which testimony may be given on videotape or not at all (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>In an effort to get civil trials to court more quickly, a State Supreme Court committee issued rules that as of last week restrict more than one trial postponement if an expert witnesses is not available. After that, the expert's testimony may be given on videotape or not at all. Although videotaping has been allowed for 20 years, some lawyers say videotaped evidence lacks the impact of live witnesses.</p>
        <p>John Holl</p>
      </block>
